9 Smokers and 6 matched non-smokers were measured with fMRI while performing an orientation affordance task [4].
FTND (Test for nicotine dependence) was applied to assess the severity of nicotine dependence. A visual and motor localizer task was applied for ROI analysis.
We used an event-related design with jittered ISI.
MRI parameters: TR = 2500 ms, 40 Slices, Slice thickness = 2.4 mm, gap thickness = 0.792 mm.

Our preliminary results suggested that compatibility between responding hand and orientation of the graspable part of smoking-related objects activated brain regions implicated in action knowledge, motor planning and perception.

This demonstrates that smoking cue reactivity involves not only subcortical but also cortical regions. Furthermore, automatized action schemata in smokers are encoded by brain regions involved in perceptual and motor processes.
Future directions:
ROI based analysis, ANCOVA with FTND Scores and Affordance Index, Cortex based alignment.
- Motives for smoking: Automaticity, Craving, Positive Reinforcement, Loss of control etc [1].
- Habitual mechanisms gain more control in the later stages of addiction [2].
- Automatized action schemata ensure fast and efficent initiation of drug use behavior in the presence of conditioned stimuli [3].
- We used fMRI and a behavioral affordance paradigm [4] to investigate neural and behavioral correlates of automatized drug taking actions in nicotine dependence [5].
